sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE GO TOP AFTER INNINGS WIN.
On Friday, West Indian all-rounder Phil Simmons made four for 38 for Leicestershire to beat Somerset by an innings and 39 runs in two days to take the lead in the county championship.

Their stay at the top, however, may be short-lived as title rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey all came close to victory, while Kent made up for lost time in their rain-affected match against Nottinghamshire.

After dismissing Somerset for 83 on the opening morning at Grace Road, Leicestershire extended their first innings by 94 runs before being bowled out for 296 with England discard Andy Caddick taking three for 83.
Trailing by 213, Somerset got off to a solid start in their second innings before Simmons intervened to dismiss them for 174.
Essex, however, look confident of regaining their top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such gave them a firm grip on their match against Yorkshire at Headingley.
Hussain, considered surplus to England's one-day needs, scored 158, his first Championship century of the season, as Essex reached 372 and took a first innings lead of 82.
By the close, Yorkshire had turned that into a 37-run lead, but bowler Such had dashed their hopes, taking four for 24 in 48 balls and leaving them hanging on 119 for five and praying for rain.

At The Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another man discarded by England, continued to silence his critics by following up his four for 45 on Thursday with 80 not out on Friday in the match against Warwickshire.
He was well supported by England hopeful Mark Butcher, who made 70, as Surrey closed on 429 for seven, a lead of 234.
Derbyshire stayed in the hunt for their first championship title since 1936 by reducing Worcestershire to 133 for five in their second innings, still 100 runs short of avoiding an innings defeat.
Australia's Tom Moody made six for 82, but Chris Adams, with 123, and Tim O'Gorman, with 109, took Derbyshire to 471 and a first-innings lead of 233.
After the frustration of seeing the opening day of their match badly affected by the weather, Kent stepped up to dismiss Nottinghamshire for 214.
They held on thanks to Paul Johnson's brave 84, but former England fast bowler Martin McCague made four for 55.
By the time the match ended, Kent had reached 108 points for three.

The world's most expensive footballer, Alan Shearer, was named England's new captain on Friday.
The 26-year-old, who joined Newcastle for £15 million ($23.4 million), takes over from Tony Adams, who led the team during the European Championship in June, and former captain David Platt.
Adams and Platt are injured and will miss England's first World Cup qualifier against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer takes over the captaincy on a trial basis, but new manager Glenn Hoddle said he saw no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton skipper should not make the job his own.
"I'm sure there won't be any problems, I'm sure Alan is the right man for the job," Hoddle said.
"There were three or four people who could have done it, but when I spoke to Alan he was up for it and really wanted it.
"In four days it is very difficult to come to a 100 per cent conclusion on something like this....
But he knows how to behave, his team-mates respect him and he knows the team's situation even if he plays up front. "
Teddy Sheringham, Shearer's strike partner at Euro 96, withdrew from the squad with an injury on Friday.
He is likely to be replaced by Les Ferdinand, Shearer's Newcastle team-mate.

FOOTBALL - ROTOR FANS BLOCKED AFTER VIOLENCE IN VOLGOGRAD.

Volgograd Rotor must play their next home game behind closed doors after fans threw bottles and stones at Dynamo Moscow players during Saturday's 1-0 home defeat, which ended Rotor's brief spell as league leaders.
The head of the Russian league's disciplinary committee, Anatoly Gorokhovsky, said on Friday that Rotor would play Lada Togliatti with empty stands on September 3.
The club, which knocked Manchester United out of last year's UEFA Cup, was fined $1,000.
Despite the defeat, Rotor are well placed with 11 games to go in the championship.
Three points behind Alania and two points behind Dynamo Moscow, the Volgograd side have one game in hand on the leaders and two more than the Moscow club.
BOXING - PANAMA'S ROBERTO DURAN FIGHTS THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Manos de Piedra" takes to the ring on Saturday in another attempt to maintain his long career.
Duran, 45, will face little-known Mexican Ariel Cruz, 30, in a non-title super middleweight bout in Panama City.
The fight, Duran's first in his home country for 10 years, is billed here as the "return of the legend" and Duran is still talking as if he is in his prime.
This match is to prepare me.
I'm not going to retire," Durán told Reuters.

But people close to the boxer acknowledge that the man who has won championships in four different weight classes - lightweight, welterweight, junior middleweight and middleweight - is nearing the end of his career.
"Every time he fights, he is on the last frontier of his career.
If he loses on Saturday, it could devalue his position as one of the great boxers in the world," said Ramon Manzanares, president of the Panamanian Boxing Association.
Duran, whose 97-12 record spans three decades, hopes a win in the 10-round bout will earn him a rematch against Puerto Rico's Hector "Macho" Camacho.
Camacho took a controversial points decision against the Panamanian in Atlantic City in June in a title fight.

TENNIS - TARANGO AND O'BRIEN SPRING A SURPRISE UNDER THE LIGHTS.
Andre Agassi escaped disaster on Thursday, but Wimbledon finalist MaliVai Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so lucky on a night of upsets at the US Open.
The 11th seed in Washington was unable to repeat his miraculous comeback at Wimbledon as he lost to wildcard Alex O'Brien 6-3 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 in a two hour and 51 minute battle on Stadium Court.
Next door in the stands, 10th seed Rios lost to another player with a Wimbledon connection: bad boy Jeff Tarango.
The temperamental left-hander defeated the Chilean 6-4 4-6 7-6 6-2.
The day's programme went smoothly, although former champion Agassi, seeded sixth, had to dig himself out of a dangerous 3-6 0-4 deficit, winning 18 of the last 19 games against India's Leander Paes.
But the night belonged to the upstarts.
Washington, who came back from a 1-5, two-set deficit in the third set against Todd Martin in the Wimbledon semi-finals, looked set for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, winner a fortnight ago in New Haven of his first professional title, served for the match at 5-4 in the third set before Washington came from behind.
"I kept saying to myself, 'keep giving yourself the best chance to win, keep fighting, maybe something will happen'," said O'Brien, 26, ranked 65th.
"I kept my composure and I was proud of myself for that; normally I would have folded up the tent and gone home."
The tough O'Brien, a former US collegiate national champion, hit 17 aces to eventually subdue the immovable Washington.
The fifth set remained on serve until the sixth game, when Washington, after saving a break point with a forehand winner down the line, netted a backhand winner to give O'Brien a 4-2 lead.
The Texan hit two aces to hold serve at 5-2 and then converted his eighth match point for the win when Washington found the net with another 40-0 backhand winner.
"You just have to keep fighting and keep trying to make him play a little bit.
I think it got a little tense at a couple of points," Washington said.
But I think it served quite well when it had to. "

Tarango, whose tantrum at Wimbledon two years ago earned him a $28,000 fine and suspension from this year's tournament at the All-England Club, disputed calls and taunted fans in his lively two-hour, 24-minute tango with Rios in the stands.
A boisterous cheering section supported the distracted Chilean and booed the lanky American, who ate up all the attention.
"I'm an emotional player," said Tarango, who is ranked 104th in the rankings. "
I think I played very well tonight, very focused. "
The match was decided in a third-set tiebreak, which the American won 7-5 to the dismay of the spectators.
"I love being booed by the public every day.
It encourages me, it makes me play my best tennis," Tarango said.
"I played some of my best tennis in college when fraternities were pouring beer on me.
If tennis was like this every day, I think everyone would have a lot more fun. "
Ríos did not like Tarango's antics.
"He always complains too much," Rios said. "
But I don't think that's what it is.
I think I played very badly.
It was difficult to play at night.
The balls were going very fast.
I have lost too many points that I never lose.
"I don't see the ball as I see it during the day.
I play American and that's why I play at night.
I didn't feel good on the court. "
At the end of the match, Tarango blew sarcastic kisses to the crowd, then shook his body at a section of Rios supporters in a mocking salute.
"I support their enthusiasm," Tarango said of the fans. "
At the same time, they are blatantly cheering against me.
After winning, I thought I could give them a bit of a shine. "
Randall Cunningham, the National Football League's all-time leader at quarterback and one of the most athletic players to ever line up under centre, retired Thursday.
Cunningham played his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
A three-time Pro Bowl selection, Cunningham rushed for 4,482 yards on 677 carries.
"I would like to thank the Eagles organization and the wonderful Philadelphia fans for supporting me throughout my career," Cunningham said.
"Although I'm sad to leave, I'm looking forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other interests that have been on the back burner for some time.
"Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie said. "
During his 11 years in Philadelphia, Randall was the cornerstone of the Eagles franchise and provided many great moments for fans in Philadelphia and throughout the NFL. "
A second-round pick in 1985, Cunningham completed 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7%) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has already been signed on as a broadcaster.
